  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `1.6.6-beta`\r\nOS & Version: Linux Mint\r\nCommit hash : (if `develop`)\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nAs far as i understand, when i sign a hased message, the resulting signature should look somewhat like this:\r\n\r\n`0x1bf6f2191550a94cdf3eb807dfda63076f8b8a6628b4e033190c131e30cb074dc976e707117e71e7328ed19ae4527b3d32ee0c0f11dcf2727ec961b825c1a1b047\"`\r\n\r\nNote, how at the end, there is no \"00\", like numerous documentations are saying, but an \"1b\", which is hexadecimal for 27.\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\nInstead, i get this `0x1be8918f888057a3604074d2fbbaf8967a6ed28f2dbac76ee6a40cb72dcd56424837eb520d33c51dd0128c994837ab4b7dbcf384096ba1bfcc02e845d1844f946a`\r\n\r\nHere, the 1b is at the beginning of the resulting signature. No matter what i sign, the first 2 chars are always 1b or 1c (27 or 28)\r\n\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n\r\nI don't know what causes this behavior. The geth i'm running on my personal machine runs fine. It's a geth version thats running on my university that acts this strange.\r\n\r\n#### Backtrace\r\n\r\n````\r\n[backtrace]\r\n````\r\n",
